Ridley Scott & crew have created, what is in my opinion, a masterpiece for science fiction lovers who tend to lean more toward the science side of fiction.  I left the theater invigorated, uplifted & inspired.  If plausible science fiction is your thing, even a little bit, then see this film!

One of the best, and worst, aspects of the book was that Marc was so cute and funny (he could be because everything was written after the fact in his journal logs) that it kind of deflated any tension or emotion the film could build. From the trailer, it looks like this film may have solved a lot of these problems. We see shots of Marc, the crew, and Jeff Daniels (Venkat? Talk about white-washing) all looking forlorn and scared which helps provide weight and illustrates how impossible the mission is. It also looks like the airlock scene is kept in the film where his helmet cracks. That might be the best scene. I also hope they do a montage where Marc tricks out the rover to the song 'Stayin' Alive', but then the montage ends when he shorts out the pathfinder.

Also, I imagined the Hab and Hermes to be a fraction of the size this trailer shows them to be.

Comment: One of the greatest challenges for any manned Mars mission isn't surviving the planet itself, but remaining mentally sound on the way there -- you don't want to freak out during a months-long space voyage. And it looks like the producers behind the movie adaptation of The Martian are well aware of this practical reality. They've posted a teaser clip showing how the fictional NASA crew copes with 10 days of isolation training meant to simulate the disconnection they'll likely experience during the journey. As you'll see below, some of them handle it better than others. A few are practically itching to go on the expedition, while others clearly... suffered a bit. Why does Aquaman have control over whales?

Comment: I am really looking forward to watching this movie. I have always been a fan of Matt Damon, and his first take as an astronaut alongside the central character that Jessica Chastain portrayed in "Interstellar" highly impressed me. Here, "The Martian" pairs them for a second time, with Damon again playing a central role as a stranded astronaut alone on a planet millions of miles from Earth. With Jeff Daniels, Sean Bean, Danny Glover, Kate Mara, and Kristen Wiig rounding out the team under the direction of the original outer space filmmaking master Ridley Scott, both the proven cast and Director together legitimize high expectations for a terrific, smart, suspenseful journey into the Unknown.

Comment:
EDIT!! [Jun. 19]
Reading only the first part of this post may communicate (sometimes very strongly) something other than what I'm saying. So please, set aside responding to felt offense until after having read (not skim) the whole thing. Thank you.
<><><><>

I'm a Psychology major, having taken multiple classes in psychology, participated in labs, interact with my professors, and overall study the science. As such, I can tell you:

--- If there is anything that science has shown us, it is that `helping others` is NOT a base instinct. What IS our base instinct is `wanting to be right` and `wanting to be liked`.

Sometimes this manifests as helping others in danger. Sometimes this manifests as punching that jerk in the face. And retaliating to being hurt by hurting back is much, MUCH more common, and more immediate a desire; it is instinctual.

We want to believe that we're good on an instinctual level, but this can only be believed in blind faith. We don't even need psychology to prove the opposite. Our every experience of wanting to respond to being hurt by hurting back proves that our instincts will destroy us.

We all know this. However, we want to deny it.

For some people, the message behind this movie will make it easier to believe that we are "mostly good". However, that will ensnare some people, making it harder for them to break the addiction to thinking themselves "mostly good", which leads to confusion and mental suffering. I am intimately aware of this in my own past and in the lives of many others.

Let's help one another! Let's try to save people in danger, and heal people who are hurting. Let us fight our natural instinct -- which is `hurting back` -- and instead forgive each other. We don't need this blind faith in ourselves in order to do good. That's a cop-out, and can trap hurting people where they are, keeping them from seeking out the help that they need.

What we need to do, is choose to love.

And when it gets too hard to love, let your weakness prove your need for strength from outside yourself, and go seek it out.

"Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest. Take my yoke upon you, and learn from me, for I am gentle and lowly in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. For my yoke is easy, and my burden is light." -- Jesus, in Matthew 11:28-30

Title: The Martian | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Amazing looking movie...

TERRIBLE TRAILER!

A trailer ¬†is supposed to get you excited... Share the overall mood of the movie.

Not spoil key plot elements.¬†

This trailer reveals that :

1) Matt manages to stay alive longer then what the MARS "base" was intended too by growing plants 

2) That he manages to send a message back to NASA

3) That his crew are turning back to get him and are likely to be the ones saving him at the end of the movie.

Was it so hard to make a simple trailer with Matt being just stuck on MARS and trying to figure out a way to survive? Was it really necessary to reveal all this stuff?

How are we suppose to feel any tension and excitement when actually watching the full movie when we already know so much about how it?

I mean... If this was like the third trailer, at least I could tell myself (Ok, already watched the teaser and first trailer. I don't need to watch more and risk being spoiled).

But this is THE FIRST TRAILER! It's not even a teaser... It's a TRAILER!

This isn't as bad as the latest terminator trailers, but still... They should find a guy who understands that trailers are not supposed to give away major spoilers and stick with him when it comes to making trailers.

The only way the movie can surprise me at this point is if Matt ends up building his own freaking spaceship to get off mars or that aliens come and save him... which are both unlikely.

I am still going to see it, but the trailer is likely to ruin a good half of the excitement I could get out of this movie.

It's about time movies started getting into space exploration while being decently produced. Was worried Interstellar was going to be the last in my lifetime. Although, even though Avatar was fiction, as was Interstellar, both did well bringing actual science to the game. Even though Avatar had much more theoretical biological science, clearly. Sound in space sadly was and still is a common plague to science fiction movies/games. Kinda kills the mood for me personally when missiles in space battles cause big flaming, smokey, explosions and then everything is on fire including the exterior of the ship. Unless the force field contains its own atmosphere, which at that point, why not just walk around on the outside of the ship without a space suit?

Whatever, the most interesting part of the movie/books to me will be/was the agricultural situation he finds himself in. As a chemistry nerd, Quick fact: the atmosphere of Mars consists of about 96% carbon dioxide. Guess what many plants on earth require to grow...????

Title: The Martian | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: The premise of this movie is ridiculous. There is no way a dust storm's winds could be strong enough to compromise a Mission. While winds could get up to 400 km/h (250 mph), the pressure at sea level on mars is 600 pascals (.087 psi) and the pressure at sea level at earth is 101.3 kilopascals (14.69 psi). To give an earth equivalent, the effective wind speed would be a light 2.36 km/h (1.475) on Earth. This is definitely not enough to throw rocks around, as shown in the trailer. The only possible danger would be dust kicked up by the storm destroying equipment, but we have pretty thoroughly solved that sort of problem, as demonstrated by our incredibly long lasting rovers. It would be a pretty crappy mission to be taken out by that sort of thing. source: (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atmosphere_of_Mars)

Title: The Martian | Teaser Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
YES! I read the entire book cover to cover in 2 days a few months ago. After reading it I had a few fears. I was afraid Matt Damon was not going to be a good Mark Watney, I was afraid they would not be able to capture the humor of the book (which for me was the best part and set the book aside from any other survival story) and I was afraid they would Hollywood it up, leaving something that bore only a passing resemblance to the book I loved so much..

This trailer has laid those fears to rest. Aside from the sign he used to contact Nasa, I could look at every scene in this trailer and tell you where it happened in the book. And while I wish I saw more funny parts from the book, I can honestly say that Matt Damon is a lot better in this role than I expected, based soley off the trailer. Can't wait.

Watched the first few seconds, will watch the rest once I've read the book.

Sorry to be a pendant, but it is a pity they didn't deal with Mars' lower gravity. If Andy Weir spent a lot of time working out the practicalities of survival on Mars, the fact that 100kg of mass on Mars has the same gravitational force on it as 38kg would do on Earth would factor into the story.

However, for stories to be effective they don't have to be accurate or literal, they have to be emotionally true. The emotional tack of this trailer is promising for the film.
